ica]]\n[[Category:Nymphalidae genera]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Johan Christian Fabricius]]\n", "name_user": "2601:587:301:4880:5d0d:6ab3:7dde:1c84", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(Your life forever)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morpho"}
{"title_page": "Emilia Clarke", "text_new": "{{Short description|British actress}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Emilia Clarke\n| image              = Emilia Clarke by Gage Skidmore 2 (cropped).jpg <!-- Please discuss on talk page before changing infobox image -->\n| caption            = Clarke at the 2013 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name         = Emilia Isobel <!-- Do not change to \"Isabelle\"; see provided source --> Euphemia Rose Clarke\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=y|1986|10|23}}\n| birth_place        = [[London]], England\n| nationality        = British\n| education          = {{unbulleted list|[[Rye St Antony School]]|[[St Edward's School, Oxford]]}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Drama Centre London]]\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 2009\u2013present\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Emilia Clarke|Full list]]\n}}\n'''Emilia Isobel <!-- Do not change to \"Isabelle\"; see provided source --> Euphemia Rose Clarke''' (born 23 October 1986) is an English actress. She studied at the [[Drama Centre London]], appearing in a number of stage productions, including one by the [[Company of Angels]]. Her television debut came with a guest appearance in an episode of the British medical soap opera ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'' in 2009. The following year, she was named as one of the \"UK Stars of Tomorrow\" by ''[[Screen International]]'' magazine for her role in the [[Syfy]] film ''[[Triassic Attack]]'' (2010).\n\nClarke rose to prominence for her breakthrough role as [[Daenerys Targaryen]] in the [[HBO]] fantasy television series ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' (2011\u20132019). The role has garnered her critical acclaim, international recognition, and [[List of awards and nominations received by Emilia Clarke|several accolades]], including four [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations. Three were for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series]], with the fourth nomination being for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series]] in 2019.\n\nClarke made her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut as Holly Golightly in a production of ''[[Breakfast at Tiffany's (novella)|Breakfast at Tiffany's]]'' in 2013 in addition to a [[West End theatre|West End]] production of ''[[The Seagull]]'' in 2020. Her film roles include [[Sarah Connor (Terminator)|Sarah Connor]] in the science fiction film ''[[Terminator Genisys]]'' (2015) and [[Qi'ra]] in the ''[[Star Wars]]'' film ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]'' (2018). She has also starred in the romantic films ''[[Me Before You (film)|Me Before You]]'' (2016) and ''[[Last Christmas (film)|Last Christmas]]'' (2019). In 2018, she was honoured by the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] with the British Artist of the Year award. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine named her one of the [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]] in 2019.\n\n==Early life==\nClarke was born on 23 October 1986 in London.<ref name=\"NY-Surgery\" /><ref name=\"apbirthday\">{{cite web |title=Celebrity birthdays for the week of Oct. 21-27 |url=https://apnews.com/e39e1935dc5e471d9c6db33e298f277c |website=[[Associated Press]] |date=15 October 2018 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626213550/https://www.apnews.com/e39e1935dc5e471d9c6db33e298f277c |archivedate=26 June 2019 |quote=Actress Emilia Clarke (''Game of Thrones'') is 32 |url-status=live}}</ref> She grew up in [[Oxfordshire]].<ref name=\"SMH\">{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/emilia-clarke-life-after-game-of-thrones-20180517-p4zfss.html|title=Emilia Clarke: Life after Game of Thrones |first=Cosima |last=Marriner|date=17 May 2018 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |publisher=[[Nine Entertainment Co.]]|access-date=14 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180914094339/https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/emilia-clarke-life-after-game-of-thrones-20180517-p4zfss.html |archive-date=14 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Her father was a theatre [[sound engineer]] from [[Wolverhampton]],<ref name=\"Vogue\">{{cite news|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/arts-and-lifestyle/2015/06/emilia-clarke-interview-may-2015-issue|title=In Vogue: Emilia Clarke |work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=15 June 2015 |accessdate=2 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151027053116/http://www.vogue.co.uk/arts-and-lifestyle/2015/06/emilia-clarke-interview-may-2015-issue|archive-date=27 October 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> while her mother is the vice-president for marketing at a global management consultancy firm as of 2020.<ref name=\"NY-Surgery\" /> Clarke also has an older brother.<ref name=\"Elle\">{{cite news|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a46307/emilia-clarke-elle-august-2017-profile/ |title=Emilia Clarke Was Born to Rule |date=26 July 2017 |work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] |publisher=[[Hearst Communications]] |access-date=28 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529054031/https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a46307/emilia-clarke-elle-august-2017-profile/ |archive-date=29 May 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Clarke said she became interested in acting at the age of three after seeing the musical ''[[Show Boat]]''.<ref name=\"now\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nowmagazine.co.uk/tv-news/game-of-thrones-star-emilia-clarke-i-feel-just-like-khaleesi-in-real-life-4889 |title=Game of Thrones star Emilia Clarke: I feel just like Khaleesi in real life |work=[[Now (UK magazine)|Now]] |publisher=[[TI Media]] |accessdate=10 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712061748/http://www.nowmagazine.co.uk/tv-news/game-of-thrones-star-emilia-clarke-i-feel-just-like-khaleesi-in-real-life-4889|archive-date=12 July 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> When she was ten, her father took her to a [[West End theatre|West End]] audition for the musical ''[[The Goodbye Girl (musical)|The Goodbye Girl]]'', a musical by [[Neil Simon]].<ref name=\"NY-Surgery\" /> Clarke attended [[Rye St Antony School]] in [[Headington]] and [[St Edward's School, Oxford]], which she left in 2005.<ref name=\"SES\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stedwards.oxon.sch.uk/milly.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110219201421/http://www.stedwards.oxon.sch.uk/milly.html|archive-date=19 February 2011 |title=OSE to star in new HBO drama|date=14 February 2011 |website=St Edward's School}}</ref> Clarke worked and travelled for some time before entering Drama Centre London, from which she graduated in 2009.<ref name=\"morris20170722\">{{cite news|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/features/game-of-thrones-cover-story-emilia-clarke-the-queen-of-dragons-tells-all-w489550|title= 'Game of Thrones': Emilia Clarke, the Queen of Dragons, Tells All |work= [[Rolling Stone]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |date= 28 June 2017 |accessdate= 22 July 2017 |first=Alex |last=Morris |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170721164251/http://www.rollingstone.com/tv/features/game-of-thrones-cover-story-emilia-clarke-the-queen-of-dragons-tells-all-w489550 |archive-date= 21 July 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nClarke stated in a 2018 interview that her maternal grandmother was the child of a secret affair between Clarke's great-grandmother and a man from the Indian subcontinent. Her grandmother wore light makeup to hide the darker complexion she had inherited from her father. Clarke credits this background for her family's having a \"history of fighters\", saying: \"The fact that [my grandmother] had to hide her skin colour, essentially, and try desperately to fit in with everyone else must've been incredibly difficult.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/05/emilia-clarke-cover-story |title=Emilia Clarke's Solo Flight |accessdate=29 May 2018 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180601175455/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/05/emilia-clarke-cover-story |archive-date=1 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Early career (2000\u20132010) ===\nClarke started to act in stage productions while attending school. She appeared in student productions of ''[[Twelfth Night]]'' and ''[[West Side Story]]'' while attending St Edward's School.<ref name=\"biographycom\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.biography.com/actor/emilia-clarke |title=Emilia Clarke Biography |last=Biography.com Editors |website=[[Biography.com]] |publisher=[[A&E Networks]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131200643/https://www.biography.com/actor/emilia-clarke |archive-date=31 January 2020 |access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref> After taking a sabbatical year, she was accepted into Drama Centre London.<ref name=\"NY-Surgery\" /> Clarke also appeared the 2009 production of ''Sense'', co-produced by theatre company [[Company of Angels]] and Drama Centre London.<ref name=\"spotlight\">{{cite news|url=http://www.spotlight.com/7655-7861-0395|title=Spotlight: Emilia Clarke |work=[[Spotlight (company)|Spotlight]]|accessdate=27 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903103030/http://www.spotlight.com/7655-7861-0395|archive-date=3 September 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nOne of her first film roles was in ''Drop the Dog'', a [[University of London]] student short film.<ref name=\"businessinsider\">{{Cite news |last=Robinson |first=Melia |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/emilia-clarke-game-of-thrones-career-2016-5#clarke-attended-the-famed-drama-centre-london-which-counts-colin-firth-michael-fassbender-and-tom-hardy-among-its-alumni-3 |title=How Emilia Clarke went from unknown actress to Mother of Dragons on 'Game of Thrones' |date=16 May 2016 |work=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707091419/http://www.businessinsider.com/emilia-clarke-game-of-thrones-career-2016-5#clarke-attended-the-famed-drama-centre-london-which-counts-colin-firth-michael-fassbender-and-tom-hardy-among-its-alumni-3 |archive-date=7 July 2018 |publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]]}}</ref> She graduated from drama school in 2009.<ref name=\"ual\">{{Cite news |last=Castleton |first=Anna |url=https://www.arts.ac.uk/about-ual/press-office/stories/the-stars-of-game-of-thrones |title=The stars of Game of Thrones |date=16 June 2015 |work=[[University of the Arts London]] |access-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201194110/https://www.arts.ac.uk/about-ual/press-office/stories/the-stars-of-game-of-thrones |archive-date=1 February 2020}}</ref> She worked at various non-acting jobs after graduating while auditioning for roles.<ref name=\"vogueUK2015\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/emilia-clarke-interview-may-2015-issue |title=The Vogue Interview: Emilia Clarke |date=15 June 2015 |work=[[British Vogue]] |access-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407204335/https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/emilia-clarke-interview-may-2015-issue |archive-date=7 April 2019 |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]}}</ref> She starred in two commercials for the charity [[Samaritans (charity)|Samaritans]], portraying a domestic abuse victim.<ref name=\"telegraph2016\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/05/26/emilia-clarke-in-pictures/emilia-clarke-samaritans/ |title=From Doctors bit-part to Game of Thrones queen: Emilia Clarke in pictures |date=26 May 2016 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201194108/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/05/26/emilia-clarke-in-pictures/emilia-clarke-samaritans/ |archive-date=1 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nHer first credited television role was a [[bit part]] in a 2009 episode of the British soap opera ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]''.<ref name=\"insiderroles\">{{Cite news |last=Singh |first=Olivia |url=https://www.insider.com/emilia-clarke-game-of-thrones-life-career-2018-10 |title=How Emilia Clarke went from unknown actress to Mother of Dragons on 'Game of Thrones' |date=22 October 2018 |work=[[Insider Inc.]] |access-date=1 February 2020 |agency=[[Axel Springer SE]]}}</ref> Clarke was cast in her first professional film role, playing Savannah in the 2010 television film ''[[Triassic Attack]]''.<ref name=\"heavy\">{{Cite news |last=Morrow |first=Brendan |url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2017/07/emilia-clarke-roles-before-game-of-thrones/ |title=Emilia Clarke: What Had She Done Before 'Game of Thrones'? |date=16 June 2017 |work=[[Heavy.com]] |access-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201204131/https://heavy.com/entertainment/2017/07/emilia-clarke-roles-before-game-of-thrones/ |archive-date=1 February 2020}}</ref> The film was released in November 2010 on the [[Syfy]] channel in American where it received negative reviews.<ref name=\"triassicattack\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/triassic_attack |title=Triassic Attack |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430085523/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/triassic_attack |archive-date=30 April 2019 |access-date=1 February 2020}}</ref> Despite the film's reviews, she was named a \"UK Star of Tomorrow\" by the film magazine ''[[Screen International]]''.<ref name=\"screeninternational\">{{Cite news |last=Grater |first=Tom |url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/emilia-clarke-to-star-in-let-me-count-the-ways-for-the-wife-director-bankside-exclusive/5139131.article |title=Emilia Clarke to star in love story 'Let Me Count The Ways' for 'The Wife' director, Bankside, Damian Jones (exclusive) |date=8 May 2019 |work=[[Screen International]] |access-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513164311/https://www.screendaily.com/news/emilia-clarke-to-star-in-let-me-count-the-ways-for-the-wife-director-bankside-exclusive/5139131.article |archive-date=13 May 2019 |publisher=Media Business Insight}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Game of Thrones'' and rise to international prominence (2011\u20132019) ===\n[[File:Emilia Clarke (9347957209).jpg|left|thumb|Clarke at the 2013 San Diego Comic-Con]]\nClarke was cast in her third professional role as [[Daenerys Targaryen]] in the [[HBO]] [[fantasy]] series ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', based on the book series ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire]]'' by [[George R. R. Martin]] in 2010.<ref name=\"morris20170722\" /> Daenerys is one of the last surviving members of [[List of A Song of Ice and Fire characters#House Targaryen|House Targaryen]] who had ruled [[Westeros]] from the [[Iron Throne (A Song of Ice and Fire)|Iron Throne]] for nearly three hundred years prior to being ousted.<ref name=\"daenerysTHR\">{{Cite news |last=Wigler |first=Josh |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/game-thrones-everything-know-rise-daenerys-targaryen-985841 |title='Game of Thrones' Everything to Know: The Rise of Daenerys Targaryen |date=14 March 2017 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201215915/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/game-thrones-everything-know-rise-daenerys-targaryen-985841 |archive-date=1 February 2020 |publisher=[[Eldridge Industries#Media holdings|Valence Media]]}}</ref> Actress [[Tamzin Merchant]] was originally cast for the part of Daenerys.<ref name=\"yahoo\">{{Cite web |url=https://tv.yahoo.com/news/emilia-clarke-was-not-the-first-choice-to-play-daenerys-targaryen-on--game-of-thrones--201200037.html |title=Emilia Clarke Was Not the First Choice to Play Daenerys Targaryen on 'Game of Thrones' |date=30 March 2013 |website=[[Yahoo! News]] |publisher=[[Verizon Media]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020223311/http://tv.yahoo.com/news/emilia-clarke-was-not-the-first-choice-to-play-daenerys-targaryen-on--game-of-thrones--201200037.html |archive-date=20 October 2013 |access-date=18 January 2017}}</ref> After the [[Winter Is Coming|pilot episode]] was re-shot in early 2010, Merchant was replaced by Clarke.<ref name=\"insideGOT\">{{Cite news |last=Renfro |first=Kim |url=https://www.insider.com/game-of-thrones-failed-pilot-hbo-chapter-kim-renfro-book |title=How 'Game of Thrones' nearly ended before it began thanks to a disastrous pilot |date=11 October 2019 |work=[[Insider Inc.]] |access-date=1 February 2020 |publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]]}}</ref> In an interview, Clarke stated that she did the [[The Chicken (dance)|funky chicken]] and [[Robot (dance)|robot dance]] during her audition.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kevin |first=Patrick |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-funky-chicken-emilia-clarke-game-of-thrones-role-20140320,0,5052593.story |title=Did the Funky Chicken land Emilia Clarke her 'Game of Thrones' role? |date=20 March 2014 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=5 May 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426150304/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-funky-chicken-emilia-clarke-game-of-thrones-role-20140320,0,5052593.story |archive-date=26 April 2014 |publisher=[[Patrick Soon-Shiong#Investments|Nant Capital]]}}</ref> Show creators [[David Benioff]] and [[D. B. Weiss]] said they chose Clarke \"10 seconds after leaving the room\".<ref name=\"mashable\">{{Cite news |last=Joho |first=Jess |url=https://mashable.com/article/emilia-clarke-dance-robot-game-of-thrones-audition/ |title=Emilia Clarke did a fire dance move at her scariest 'Game of Thrones' audition |date=28 October 2018 |work=[[Mashable]] |access-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201222618/https://mashable.com/article/emilia-clarke-dance-robot-game-of-thrones-audition/ |archive-date=1 February 2020 |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]}}</ref> The show ran from April 2011 until May 2019, with Clarke portraying Daenerys throughout all [[List of Game of Thrones episodes|eight seasons]].<ref name=\"nytmay2019\">{{Cite news |last=Vineyard |first=Jennifer |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/22/arts/television/game-of-thrones-emilia-clarke-daenerys.html |title=Emilia Clarke: Daenerys's 'Game of Thrones' Turn 'Was a Huge Shock' |date=22 May 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190917121752/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/22/arts/television/game-of-thrones-emilia-clarke-daenerys.html |archive-date=17 September 2019 |publisher=[[A. G. Sulzberger]]}}</ref>\n\nClarke has received widespread praise for her portrayal of Daenerys, which traces an arc from frightened girl to empowered woman. Matthew Gilbert of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' called her scenes \"mesmerizing\", adding that \"Clarke doesn't have a lot of emotional variety to work with as Daenerys, aside from fierce determination, and yet she is riveting.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gilbert|first1=Matthew|title=Fantasy gets real on 'Game of Thrones'|url=https://www.boston.com/ae/tv/2013/03/28/fantasy-gets-real-game-thrones/1YgKl5ZdzVZnRzVxuonIBK/story.html|website=[[Boston Globe]]|publisher=[[John W. Henry]]|accessdate=1 May 2017|date=28 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305070704/http://www.boston.com/ae/tv/2013/03/28/fantasy-gets-real-game-thrones/1YgKl5ZdzVZnRzVxuonIBK/story.html|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Emily VanDerWerff for ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' commented on the difficulty of adapting such an evolution from page to screen, but concluded that Clarke \"more than seal[s] the deal here.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.avclub.com/articles/a-golden-crown-for-experts,56414/ |title=A Golden Crown\" (for experts) |last=VanDerWerff |first=Emily |date=22 May 2011 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |publisher=[[G/O Media]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110524074238/http://www.avclub.com/articles/a-golden-crown-for-experts,56414/ |archive-date=24 May 2011 |access-date=24 May 2011}}</ref> \n\nIn 2017, she reportedly became one of the [[List of highest paid American television stars|highest paid actors on television]], potentially earning \u00a32{{nbsp}}million per episode of ''Game of Thrones''.{{efn|''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' reported the salary per episode to be \u00a31.2{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"harpersbazaar\">{{cite news |last1=Gonzales |first1=Erica |last2=Jones |first2=Alexis |title=Game of Thrones Stars Could Be Making Millions Per Episode in the Final Season |url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/film-tv/a12048623/game-of-thrones-salaries-per-episode/ |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=[[Harper's Bazaar]] |publisher=[[Hearst Communications]] |date=1 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715191151/https://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/film-tv/a12048623/game-of-thrones-salaries-per-episode/ |archivedate=15 July 2019}}</ref> while ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' reported \u00a32{{nbsp}}million per episode.<ref name=\"thetelegraph\">{{cite news |title=Game of Thrones stars reportedly sign biggest pay-per-episode deal in TV history |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2017/04/25/game-thrones-stars-reportedly-sign-biggest-pay-per-episode-deal/ |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=25 April 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810075611/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2017/04/25/game-thrones-stars-reportedly-sign-biggest-pay-per-episode-deal/ |archivedate=10 August 2019}}</ref>}} In 2019, she said she had been uncomfortable acting nude in her first experience at age 23 of a large film set, but had since become \"a lot more savvy\" about what level of nudity is needed for a scene.<ref name=\"guardian-20191120\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/nov/20/emilia-clarke-game-of-thrones-nude-scenes-were-terrifying |title=Emilia Clarke: Game of Thrones nude scenes were 'terrifying' |date=20 November 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=20 November 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120041026/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/nov/20/emilia-clarke-game-of-thrones-nude-scenes-were-terrifying |archive-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nClarke received multiple award nominations and wins for her role of Daenerys. After the [[Game of Thrones (season 1)|first season]], Clarke won Best Supporting Actress in a Drama at the 2011 [[Entertainment Weekly#Poppy Awards|EWwy Awards]].<ref name=\"ew\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20300978_20529029,00.html#21054822 |title=EWwy Awards 2011: Meet Your Winners! |date=19 September 2011 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/66idVONuw?url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20300978_20529029,00.html#21054822#21054822 |archive-date=6 April 2012 |access-date=17 September 2011}}</ref> She was also nominated three times for Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series in 2013, 2015, and 2016.<ref name=\"televisionacademy\">{{cite web |title=Emilia Clarke |url=https://www.emmys.com/bios/emilia-clarke |website=Television Academy |publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]] |accessdate=2 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831203812/https://www.emmys.com/bios/emilia-clarke |archive-date=31 August 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[71st Primetime Emmy Awards|2019 Emmys]], she was nominated for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series, her first nomination in the category.<ref name=\"DeadlineEmmy\">{{Cite news |last=Patten |first=Dominic |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/game-of-thrones-emmy-record-nominations-kit-harington-emilia-clarke-cast-1202647028/ |title='Game Of Thrones' Emilia Clarke & Kit Harington Score 1st Ever Emmy Lead Nominations; Finale Big Hit With TV Academy, Despite Backlash |date=16 July 2019 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=2 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722040015/https://deadline.com/2019/07/game-of-thrones-emmy-record-nominations-kit-harington-emilia-clarke-cast-1202647028/ |archive-date=22 July 2019 |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]}}</ref> \n\nIn addition to the television show, she lent her voice and likeness to the 2014 [[Game of Thrones (2014 video game)|video game of the same name]].<ref name=\"gameinformer\">{{cite web |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160901123724/http://www.gameinformer.com/games/game_of_thrones_ep_1_-_iron_from_ice/b/pc/archive/2014/11/20/exclusive-meet-the-exiled-son-of-game-of-thrones-house-forrester.aspx |archivedate=1 September 2016 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/game_of_thrones_ep_1_-_iron_from_ice/b/pc/archive/2014/11/20/exclusive-meet-the-exiled-son-of-game-of-thrones-house-forrester.aspx |title=[Exclusive] Meet The Exiled Son of Game of Thrones' House Forrester |last=Futter |first=Mike |work=[[Game Informer]] |publisher=[[GameStop]] |date=20 November 2014 |accessdate=17 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> She also made a [[cameo appearance]] during [[Kit Harington]]{{'s}} monologue on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' in April 2019.<ref name=\"snl\">{{Cite news |last=Andrews |first=Travis |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/04/07/game-thrones-meets-saturday-night-live-when-emilia-clarke-others-crash-kit-haringtons-monologue/ |title='Game of Thrones' meets 'Saturday Night Live' when Emilia Clarke and others crash Kit Harington's monologue |date=7 April 2019 |work=[[Washington Post]] |access-date=2 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410112950/https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/04/07/game-thrones-meets-saturday-night-live-when-emilia-clarke-others-crash-kit-haringtons-monologue/ |archive-date=10 April 2019 |publisher=[[Fred Ryan]]}}</ref> She said in a November 2019 [[NPR]] interview if she \"were to get stereotyped as the mother of dragons, I could ask for worse. It's really quite wonderful.\"<ref name=\"NPRinterview\">{{Cite news |last=Garcia-Navarro |first=Lulu |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/03/775510530/emilia-clarke-on-last-christmas-brexit-and-life-after-game-of-thrones |title=Emilia Clarke On 'Last Christmas,' Brexit And Life After 'Game Of Thrones' |date=3 November 2019 |work=[[NPR]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101134745/https://www.npr.org/2019/11/03/775510530/emilia-clarke-on-last-christmas-brexit-and-life-after-game-of-thrones |archive-date=1 January 2020 |publisher=National Public Radio, Inc. |quote=So I've had the good fortune of being in this incredible show with this incredible character. And my goodness, if I were to get stereotyped as the mother of dragons, I could ask for worse. It's really quite wonderful.}}</ref>\n\n=== Film career (2012\u2013present) ===\nClarke's first film role was in the short film ''[[Shackled (2012 British film)|Shackled]]'' (2012).<ref name=\"filmshortage\">{{cite web |title=Shackled |url=https://filmshortage.com/shorts/shackled/ |website=Film Shortage |accessdate=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190627004259/https://filmshortage.com/shorts/shackled/ |archive-date=27 June 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The same year, she starred alongside [[Elliott Tittensor]] in the comedy film ''[[Spike Island (film)|Spike Island]]''. It details a group of friends who try to get to the [[Spike Island (Cheshire)|namesake island]] of [[The Stone Roses]] 1990 concert.<ref name=\"thefilmstage\">{{Cite web |url=http://thefilmstage.com/news/lesley-manville-and-emilia-clarke-travel-to-spike-island-with-the-stone-roses/ |title=Lesley Manville and Emilia Clarke Travel to 'Spike Island' With The Stone Roses |date=9 February 2012 |website=The Film Stage |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130411235638/http://thefilmstage.com/news/lesley-manville-and-emilia-clarke-travel-to-spike-island-with-the-stone-roses/ |archive-date=11 April 2013 |access-date=15 June 2013}}</ref> The movie was originally distributed only in the United Kingdom but was subsequently picked up by Level 33 Entertainment for North American distribution in spring 2015.<ref>{{Cite news |last=McNary |first=Dave |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/emilia-clarke-spike-island-us-distribution-1201459590/ |title=Emilia Clarke's 'Spike Island' Set for U.S. Distribution by Level 33 |date=25 March 2015 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711103621/https://variety.com/2015/film/news/emilia-clarke-spike-island-us-distribution-1201459590/ |archive-date=11 July 2015 |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]}}</ref> From March to April 2013, she played Holly Golightly in a Broadway production of ''[[Breakfast at Tiffany's (novella)|Breakfast at Tiffany's]]'', a role requiring her to perform a nude scene.<ref name=\"broadway.com\">{{Cite news |last=Marc |first=Snetiker |url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/168117/emilia-clarke-on-breakfast-at-tiffanys-nudity-game-of-thrones-fans-being-a-single-girl-in-nyc/ |title=Emilia Clarke on Breakfast at Tiffany's Nudity, Game of Thrones Fans & Being a Single Girl in NYC |date=18 March 2013 |work=[[John Gore Organization|#Assets|Broadway.com]] |access-date=13 October 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328220128/https://www.broadway.com/buzz/168117/emilia-clarke-on-breakfast-at-tiffanys-nudity-game-of-thrones-fans-being-a-single-girl-in-nyc/ |archive-date=28 March 2020 |publisher=John Gore Organization}}</ref> The production, along with her performance, received mixed reviews from critics.<ref name=\"thrBAT\">{{Cite news |last=Rooney |first=David |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/theater-review-breakfast-at-tiffanys-429993 |title='Breakfast at Tiffany's': Theater Review |date=3 March 2013 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323214020/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/theater-review-breakfast-at-tiffanys-429993 |archive-date=23 March 2013 |publisher=[[Eldridge Industries#Media holdings|Valence Media]]}}</ref><ref name=\"broadwayworld\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/reviews/Breakfast-at-Tiffany-s |title=BREAKFAST AT TIFFANY'S Broadway Reviews |website=[[BroadwayWorld]] |publisher=Wisdom Digital Media |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204192949/https://www.broadwayworld.com/reviews/Breakfast-at-Tiffany-s |archive-date=4 February 2020 |access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref> Later that year, she also starred in the [[black comedy]]-crime drama film ''[[Dom Hemingway]]'' alongside [[Jude Law]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Plumb |first1=Ali |title=Dom Hemingway Pic Sees Jude Law And Richard E. Grant Stuck In The '70s |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/dom-hemingway-pic-sees-jude-law-richard-e-grant-stuck-70s/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]] |date=24 July 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424222150/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/dom-hemingway-pic-sees-jude-law-richard-e-grant-stuck-70s/ |archivedate=24 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Emilia Clarke (49589951248).jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|left|Clarke at the [[2013 Toronto International Film Festival]]|alt=Actress Emilia Clarke at the 2013 Toronto Film Festival]]\n\nIn May 2013, Clarke was cast in a film adaptation of the novel ''[[The Garden of Last Days]]''.<ref name=\"vulture\">{{Cite news |last=Lyons |first=Margaret |url=https://www.vulture.com/2013/05/emilia-clarke-cast-in-james-francos-new-movie.html |title=Emilia Clarke Cast in James Franco's New Movie |date=2 May 2013 |work=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707024945/https://www.vulture.com/2013/05/emilia-clarke-cast-in-james-francos-new-movie.html |archive-date=7 July 2013 |publisher=[[Vox Media]]}}</ref> [[James Franco]] was set to direct and star in the film however he left the project two weeks before filming after creative differences with the film distributor [[Alchemy (company)|Millennium Entertainment]].<ref name=\"deadline2016\">{{Cite news |last=Fleming Jr. |first=Mike |url=https://deadline.com/2013/06/garden-of-last-days-scrapped-as-directorstar-james-franco-exits-two-weeks-before-shooting-531327/ |title='Garden Of Last Days' Scrapped As Director-Star James Franco Exits Two Weeks Before Shooting |date=27 June 2016 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203184727/https://deadline.com/2013/06/garden-of-last-days-scrapped-as-directorstar-james-franco-exits-two-weeks-before-shooting-531327/ |archive-date=3 February 2016 |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]}}</ref> In an 2019 interview with ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', Clarke said she was offered the role of Anastasia Steele in ''[[Fifty Shades of Grey (film)|Fifty Shades of Grey]]''.<ref name=\"ew2019\">{{Cite news |last=Huff |first=Lauren |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/05/23/emilia-clarke-fifty-shades-of-grey-game-of-thrones-nudity/ |title=Emilia Clarke turned down Fifty Shades of Grey after feeling 'pigeonholed' by Game of Thrones nudity |date=23 May 2019 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524003749/https://ew.com/tv/2019/05/23/emilia-clarke-fifty-shades-of-grey-game-of-thrones-nudity/ |archive-date=24 May 2019 |publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]}}</ref> She said she turned down the part because of the nudity required.<ref name=\"huffpost50\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/03/25/emilia-clarke-fifty-shades_n_6940586.html |title='Game of Thrones' Star Emilia Clarke Turned Down 'Fifty Shades of Grey' |date=25 March 2015 |website=[[HuffPost]] |publisher=[[Verizon Media]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003131758/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/03/25/emilia-clarke-fifty-shades_n_6940586.html |archive-date=3 October 2015 |access-date=13 September 2015}}</ref> \n\nIn 2013, she was cast as [[Sarah Connor (Terminator)|Sarah Connor]] in the science fiction action film ''[[Terminator Genisys]]'' (2015). The film, which also stars [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]], [[Jai Courtney]], and [[Jason Clarke]], received unfavourable reviews from critics,<ref name=\"RTterminator\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/terminator_genisys/ |title=Terminator Genisys |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601235647/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/terminator_genisys |archive-date=1 June 2017 |access-date=27 April 2017}}</ref> Despite the reviews, the movie was a box office success, grossing over $440{{nbsp}}million worldwide.<ref name=\"BOMterminator\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt1340138/?ref_=bo_se_r_4 |title=Terminator Genisys (2015) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[IMDb]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104141519/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt1340138/?ref_=bo_se_r_4 |archive-date=4 November 2019 |access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref> Clarke was nominated for [[2015 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Award for Choice Summer Movie Star \u2013 Female]] and Best International Actress at the 2016 [[Jupiter Award (film award)#38th Jupiter Award / 2016|Jupiter Awards]] for her performance.<ref name=\"VarietyTCA\">{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/teen-choice-awards-winners-2015-full-list-1201571268/ |title=Teen Choice Awards 2015 Winners: Full List |date=16 August 2015 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327134333/https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/teen-choice-awards-winners-2015-full-list-1201571268/ |archive-date=27 March 2019 |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]}}</ref>\n\nShe starred as the female lead, opposite [[Sam Claflin]], in the movie adaption of the best-selling book of the same name, ''[[Me Before You (film)|Me Before You]]''. The film which was released on 3 June 2016 and directed by [[Thea Sharrock]], received mixed critical reviews.<ref name=\"RTmebeforeyou\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/me_before_you |title=Me Before You |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830153208/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/me_before_you/ |archive-date=30 August 2019 |access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref> The film grossed $200{{nbsp}}million worldwide and was a box office success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/09/me-before-you-passes-200-million-worldwide-box-office-emilia-clarke-sam-claflin-1201813713/|title='Me Before You' Crosses $200M At Worldwide Box Office On $20M Budget|last=Tartaglione|first=Nancy|last2=Tartaglione|first2=Nancy|date=6 September 2016|website=Deadline|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> For her role as Louisa Clark, she shared nominations with Sam Claflin for the [[2016 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Liplock]] and the [[2017 MTV Movie & TV Awards|MTV Television Tearjerker Award]].<ref name=\"eonlineTCA\">{{Cite news |last=Vulpo |first=Mike |url=https://www.eonline.com/news/784000/teen-choice-awards-2016-winners-the-complete-list |title=Teen Choice Awards 2016 Winners: The Complete List |date=31 July 2016 |work=[[E!|E! News]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803000635/https://www.eonline.com/news/784000/teen-choice-awards-2016-winners-the-complete-list |archive-date=3 August 2016 |publisher=[[NBCUniversal Cable Entertainment Group]]}}</ref><ref name=\"mtv2017\">{{cite news |last1=Morin |first1=Natalie |title=2017 MTV Movie & TV Awards Winners: See the Full List |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3009781/2017-mtv-movie-tv-awards-winners-list/ |accessdate=4 February 2020 |publisher=[[MTV News]] |date=7 May 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170512015457/http://www.mtv.com/news/3009781/2017-mtv-movie-tv-awards-winners-list/ |archivedate=12 May 2017}}</ref> In 2017, she played the lead as Nurse Verena in the supernatural psychological thriller film ''[[Voice from the Stone]]''. The film was released in April 2017 for a [[limited release|limited]] theatre run, followed by [[video on demand]] and digital HD.<ref name=\"varietyVFTS\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/emilia-clarke-voice-from-the-stone-1201221309/ |title='Game of Thrones' Star Emilia Clarke Set for Thriller 'Voice From the Stone' |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=16 June 2014 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180210180501/https://variety.com/2014/film/news/emilia-clarke-voice-from-the-stone-1201221309/ |archive-date=10 February 2018 |access-date=22 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nShe was cast as the female lead in ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]'' in November 2016. The movie, which was directed by [[Ron Howard]] and premiered in November 2018, details the origins of ''[[Star Wars]]'' characters [[Han Solo]] and [[Chewbacca]].<ref name=\"gqSolo\">{{Cite news |last=Meslow |first=Scott |url=https://www.gq.com/story/solo-a-star-wars-story-spoiler-review |title=Solo: A Star Wars Story, the Spoiler-Filled Review |date=25 May 2018 |work=[[GQ]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525085427/https://www.gq.com/story/solo-a-star-wars-story-spoiler-review |archive-date=25 May 2018 |publisher=[[Advance Publications]]}}</ref> Clarke played [[Qi'ra]], Han's childhood friend and love interest.<ref name=\"ewstarwars\">{{Cite news |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/02/08/emilia-clarke-solo-a-star-wars-story/ |title=Emilia Clarke says her Star Wars femme fatale 'has a core of steel' |date=8 February 2018 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414183514/https://ew.com/movies/2018/02/08/emilia-clarke-solo-a-star-wars-story/ |archive-date=14 April 2019 |publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]}}</ref> The film received favourable critical reviews despite being the second-lowest grossing ''Star Wars'' film.<ref name=\"BOMstarwars\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?view=main&id=starwars.htm&sort=gross&order=ASC&p=.htm |title=Star Wars |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[IMDb]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621072959/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?view=main&id=starwars.htm&sort=gross&order=ASC&p=.htm |archive-date=21 June 2018 |access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref> The film was released worldwide on 25 May 2018.<ref name=\"moviefone\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.moviefone.com/2016/11/18/emilia-clarke-joins-han-solo-movie-as-female-lead/ |title=Emilia Clarke Joins Han Solo Movie as Female Lead |last=Carbone |first=Gina |date=18 November 2016 |website=[[Moviefone]] |publisher=[[Helios and Matheson Analytics]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161120085403/https://www.moviefone.com/2016/11/18/emilia-clarke-joins-han-solo-movie-as-female-lead/ |archive-date=20 November 2016 |access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> Her performance received positive critical reviews with many calling her one of the standouts of the film.<ref name=\"CNETstarwars\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/solo-a-star-wars-story-best-and-worst-our-global-review/ |title=Solo: A Star Wars Story best and worst -- our global review |date=29 May 2018 |work=[[CNET]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819103219/https://www.cnet.com/news/solo-a-star-wars-story-best-and-worst-our-global-review/ |archive-date=19 August 2018 |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>\n\nClarke, along with [[Jack Huston]], was cast in 2016 as leads in the film ''[[Above Suspicion (2019 film)|Above Suspicion]]'' (2019). The film, based on a thriller novel by [[Joe Sharkey]] and directed by [[Phillip Noyce]], was announced at the [[2016 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"THRAS\">{{Cite news |last=Galuppo |first=Mia |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-emilia-clarke-jack-huston-890096 |title=Cannes: Emilia Clarke, Jack Huston to Star in Thriller 'Above Suspicion' |date=3 May 2016 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190627004310/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-emilia-clarke-jack-huston-890096 |archive-date=27 June 2019 |publisher=[[Eldridge Industries#Media holdings|Valence Media]]}}</ref> In late 2019, Clarke starred in the romantic comedy film ''[[Last Christmas (film)|Last Christmas]]''. It was a box office success, grossing $121{{nbsp}}million worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/box-office/emilia-clarke-last-christmas-box-office-milestone-1203438257/ |title=Emilia Clarke's 'Last Christmas' Crosses $100{{nbsp}}Million at Global Box Office |last=Rubin |first=Rebecca |date=15 December 2019 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl705070593/ |title=Last Christmas |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[IMDb]] |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> The film, also starring [[Henry Golding]], was written by [[Emma Thompson]] and directed by [[Paul Feig]].<ref name=\"THRchristmas\">{{Cite news |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/emilia-clarke-henry-golding-star-last-christmas-1141382 |title=Emilia Clarke, Henry Golding to Star in 'Last Christmas' (Exclusive) |date=18 September 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920081853/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/emilia-clarke-henry-golding-star-last-christmas-1141382 |archive-date=20 September 2019 |publisher=[[Eldridge Industries#Media holdings|Valence Media]]}}</ref> In a January 2020 interview with ''[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]'' magazine, Clarke stated she was inspired by [[Will Ferrell]]{{'s}} character in the 2003 comedy film ''[[Elf (film)|Elf]]''.<ref name=\"bustleinterview\">{{Cite news |last=Blanton |first=Kayla |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/emilia-clarke-challenged-will-ferrells-elf-skills-during-lie-detector-test-19766514 |title=Emilia Clarke Challenged Will Ferrell's Elf Skills During Lie Detector Test |date=5 January 2020 |work=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106165411/https://www.bustle.com/p/emilia-clarke-challenged-will-ferrells-elf-skills-during-lie-detector-test-19766514 |archive-date=6 January 2020 |publisher=Bustle Digital Group |quote=...I took as much inspiration from him as possible, though.}}</ref> Although the film received negative reviews, critics praised Clarke's performance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Roeper |first1=Richard |title='Last Christmas' gives your heart something special |url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/11/6/20951017/last-christmas-review-movie-emilia-clarke-henry-golding-emma-thompson |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |publisher=[[Sun-Times Media Group]] |date=6 November 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107034949/https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/11/6/20951017/last-christmas-review-movie-emilia-clarke-henry-golding-emma-thompson |archivedate=7 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Floyd |first1=Thomas |title=The rom-com 'Last Christmas' has a major plot twist. Sadly, it does not deliver. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/the-rom-com-last-christmas-has-a-major-plot-twist-sadly-it-does-not-deliver/2019/11/06/4fc4ddce-fc0c-11e9-8906-ab6b60de9124_story.html?arc404=true |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |publisher=[[Fred Ryan]] |date=6 November 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108203205/https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/the-rom-com-last-christmas-has-a-major-plot-twist-sadly-it-does-not-deliver/2019/11/06/4fc4ddce-fc0c-11e9-8906-ab6b60de9124_story.html?arc404=true |archivedate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Upcoming projects ====\nClarke was cast in the [[historical drama]] film ''The Guns of August'' in 2014.<ref name=\"newsweek\">{{Cite news |last=Shaffer |first=Claire |url=https://www.newsweek.com/game-thrones-cast-upcoming-projects-star-wars-x-men-639142 |title=What's Next For The 'Game Of Thrones' Cast? Upcoming Roles For Emilia Clarke, Kit Harington and More |date=19 July 2017 |work=[[Newsweek]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200119040951/https://www.newsweek.com/game-thrones-cast-upcoming-projects-star-wars-x-men-639142 |archive-date=19 January 2020 |publisher=Dev Pragad}}</ref> The movie, which is based on the [[The Guns of August|book of the same name]] and set during [[World War I]], will also star [[Helena Bonham Carter]] and ''Game of Thrones'' co-star [[Charles Dance]].<ref name=\"varietyTGOA\">{{Cite news |last=McNary |first=Dave |url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/cannes-helena-bonham-carter-charles-dance-starring-in-world-war-i-drama-1201185992/ |title=Cannes: Helena Bonham Carter, Charles Dance Starring in World War I Drama |date=19 May 2014 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160824182658/https://variety.com/2014/film/news/cannes-helena-bonham-carter-charles-dance-starring-in-world-war-i-drama-1201185992/ |archive-date=24 August 2014 |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]}}</ref> As of 2020, the film was still in pre-production.<ref name=\"deadlineTGOA\">{{Cite news |last=Fleming Jr. |first=Mike |url=https://deadline.com/2014/05/cannes-arclight-shops-oliver-hirschbiegel-wwi-pic-the-guns-of-august-732975/ |title=Cannes: Arclight Shops Oliver Hirschbiegel WWI Pic 'The Guns Of August' |date=19 May 2014 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710125521/https://deadline.com/2014/05/cannes-arclight-shops-oliver-hirschbiegel-wwi-pic-the-guns-of-august-732975/ |archive-date=10 July 2017 |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]}}</ref> In January 2017, she was cast as the lead in the upcoming English language adaptation of the 2015 Korean romantic comedy ''[[The Beauty Inside (2015 film)|The Beauty Inside]]''.<ref name=\"Beauty-Inside\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/emilia-clarke-star-beauty-inside-fox-2000-temple-hill-968891 |title=Emilia Clarke to Star in 'The Beauty Inside' for Fox 2000, Temple Hill |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |date=27 January 2017 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Eldridge Industries#Media holdings|Valence Media]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127162527/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/emilia-clarke-star-beauty-inside-fox-2000-temple-hill-968891 |archive-date=27 January 2017 |access-date=27 January 2017}}</ref> It was announced in spring 2019 that Clarke is set to play the English poet [[Elizabeth Barrett Browning|Elizabeth Barrett]] in the film ''Let Me Count the Ways'', which ''[[The Wife (2017 film)|The Wife]]'' director [[Bj\u00f6rn Runge]] is set to direct.<ref name=\"Let Me Count the Ways\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/emilia-clarke-game-of-thrones-to-star-in-bjorn-runge-directed-love-story-let-me-count-the-ways-1203208712/ |title=Emilia Clarke to Star in Bjorn Runge-Directed Love Story 'Let Me Count the Ways' |last=Clarke |first=Stewart |date=8 May 2019 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127162527/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/emilia-clarke-game-of-thrones-to-star-in-bjorn-runge-directed-love-story-let-me-count-the-ways-1203208712 |archive-date=8 May 2019 |access-date=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2019, Clarke was cast in the West End production of [[Anton Chekhov]]{{'s}} ''[[The Seagull]]''.<ref name=\"playbill2020\">{{Cite news |last=Meyer |first=Dan |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/game-of-thrones-emilia-clarke-to-make-west-end-debut-in-the-seagull |title=Game of Thrones' Emilia Clarke to Make West End Debut in The Seagull |date=20 December 2019 |work=[[Playbill]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220225234/http://www.playbill.com/article/game-of-thrones-emilia-clarke-to-make-west-end-debut-in-the-seagull |archive-date=20 December 2019 |publisher=TotalTheater}}</ref> The production, which will be directed by [[Jamie Lloyd (director)|Jamie Lloyd]], was scheduled to premiere at the [[Playhouse Theatre]] in March 2020.<ref name=\"guardianplay\">{{Cite news |last=Wiegand |first=Chris |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2019/dec/20/emilia-clarke-to-make-west-end-theatre-debut-in-the-seagull |title=Emilia Clarke to make West End theatre debut in The Seagull |date=20 December 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101090412/https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2019/dec/20/emilia-clarke-to-make-west-end-theatre-debut-in-the-seagull |archive-date=1 January 2020}}</ref> The premiere was pushed back due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"atg\">{{cite web |title=Information and Advice about the Coronavirus |url=https://www.atgtickets.com/coronavirus-info/?_ga=2.239938755.1748251278.1585531608-1280699151.1585531608 |website=ATGTickets |publisher=[[Ambassador Theatre Group]] |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archiveurl=http://archive.today/vF5Zf |archivedate=29 March 2020}}</ref> ''The Seagull'' will be Clarke's first West End production.<ref name=\"thestage\">{{Cite news |last=Lefkowitz |first=Andy |url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/197966/emilia-clarke-to-make-west-end-debut-in-new-staging-of-the-seagull/ |title=Game of Thrones star Emilia Clarke to make West End debut in The Seagull |date=20 December 2019 |access-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204180755/https://www.broadway.com/buzz/197966/emilia-clarke-to-make-west-end-debut-in-new-staging-of-the-seagull/ |archive-date=4 February 2020 |publisher=Broadway.com |agency=[[John Gore Organization]]}}</ref>\n\n== Off-screen work ==\n=== Advertising and endorsements ===\nIn 2015, luxury goods company [[Dior]] signed Clarke to be the face of the Rose des Vents jewelry collection.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Diderich |first1=Joelle |title='Game of Thrones' Actress Emilia Clarke to Front Dior Jewelry Campaign |url=https://wwd.com/business-news/media/game-of-thrones-emilia-clarke-to-front-dior-jewelry-campaign-10272728/ |accessdate=27 February 2020 |work=[[Women's Wear Daily]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |date=4 November 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180112055916/https://wwd.com/business-news/media/game-of-thrones-emilia-clarke-to-front-dior-jewelry-campaign-10272728/ |archivedate=12 January 2018}}</ref> In 2018, [[Dolce & Gabbana]] announced she would be the brand ambassador for the fragrance \"The Only One\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=March |first1=Bridget |title=Exclusive: Emilia Clarke on finding self-confidence (and the perfect red lipstick) |url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/uk/beauty/fragrance/a22908975/emilia-clarke-beauty-interview/ |accessdate=26 February 2020 |work=[[Harper's Bazaar]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines]] |date=4 September 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212225412/https://www.harpersbazaar.com/uk/beauty/fragrance/a22908975/emilia-clarke-beauty-interview/ |archivedate=12 February 2019}}</ref> She starred in an advertisement, which was directed by [[Matteo Garrone]] for the perfume.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Renfro |first=Kim |url=https://www.insider.com/emilia-clarke-new-dolce-gabbana-ad-video-2018-9 |title=Watch Emilia Clarke sing a classic Italian pop song for a new Dolce & Gabbana perfume ad |date=4 September 2018 |work=[[Insider Inc.]] |access-date=27 February 2020 |publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]]}}</ref> Cosmetics company [[Clinique]] announced Clarke as their first global ambassador in early 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Penrose |first1=Nerisha |title=Emilia Clarke Is Clinique's First-Ever Global Ambassador |url=https://www.elle.com/beauty/makeup-skin-care/a30530209/emilia-clarke-clinique-first-global-ambassador/ |accessdate=26 February 2020 |work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] |publisher=[[Hearst Communications]] |date=15 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200121120701/https://www.elle.com/beauty/makeup-skin-care/a30530209/emilia-clarke-clinique-first-global-ambassador/ |archivedate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Activism and charity work ===\nClarke also supports several charitable organisations. In September 2011, she joined the SMA UK Trust Team as their celebrity ambassador.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://smatrust.org/emilia-clarke-wows-brokers-at-annual-bgc-charity-day/|title=Emilia Clarke wows brokers at annual BGC Charity Day!|publisher=The SMA Trust|date=12 September 2015|accessdate=16 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415124825/https://smatrust.org/emilia-clarke-wows-brokers-at-annual-bgc-charity-day/|archive-date=15 April 2018}}</ref> The SMA Trust raises funds for research into [[spinal muscular atrophy]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Sma Trust |url=https://beta.charitycommission.gov.uk/charity-details?regid=1097765&subid=0 |website=[[Charity Commission for England and Wales]] |publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] |accessdate=1 April 2020 |archiveurl=http://archive.today/66WM8 |archivedate=1 April 2020}}</ref> In August 2017, she became a patron of Open Door, a non-profit that aims to help young people gain access to drama school auditions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.opendoor.org.uk/news/2017/8/26/emilia-clarke-joins-open-door-k3763 |title=Emilia and Riz join Open Door! |date=30 August 2017 |website=Open Door |publisher=Open Door |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517152640/https://www.opendoor.org.uk/news/2017/8/26/emilia-clarke-joins-open-door-k3763 |archive-date=17 May 2018 |access-date=16 May 2018}}</ref> She auctioned a chance to watch an episode of ''Game of Thrones'' with her at the 2018 Sean Penn Charity Gala, which raised over $120,000 benefiting the [[J/P Haitian Relief Organization|J/P HRO]] & Disaster Relief Organizations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/scene/news/brad-pitt-bid-120000-to-watch-game-of-thrones-with-emilia-clarke-1202655715/ |title=Brad Pitt Bid $120,000 to Watch 'Game of Thrones' With Emilia Clarke |last=Wagmeister |first=Elizabeth |date=6 January 2018 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516080722/http://variety.com/2018/scene/news/brad-pitt-bid-120000-to-watch-game-of-thrones-with-emilia-clarke-1202655715/ |archive-date=16 May 2018 |access-date=16 May 2018}}</ref> In February 2018, she introduced the award recipients at London's [[Centrepoint (charity)|Centrepoint]] Awards, which celebrates the courage shown by homeless young people.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gonzales |first1=Erica |title=The Duke of Cambridge and Mother of Dragons Hung Out Last Night |url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/celebrity/latest/a16868597/prince-william-emilia-clarke-meet/ |work=[[Harper's Bazaar]] |publisher=[[Hearst Communications]] |date=9 February 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619180659/https://www.harpersbazaar.com/celebrity/latest/a16868597/prince-william-emilia-clarke-meet/ |archivedate=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, she was named the sole ambassador to the [[Royal College of Nursing]] (RCN). As the RCN's ambassador, Clarke pledged to use her voice to fight for greater investment in nursing and to challenge misconceptions. Clarke also pledged to join nurses and healthcare workers to tackle the issues affecting the profession, including a falling number in training and shortages in the current workforce.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rcn.org.uk/news-and-events/news/game-of-thrones-star-emilia-clarke-becomes-rcn-ambassador |title=Game of Thrones star Emilia Clarke launches fundraising campaign as nursing ambassador {{!}} News {{!}} Royal College of Nursing |website=[[Royal College of Nursing]]|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nClarke was also one of the many UK based actresses to lend her voice to the [[Time's Up (movement)|Time's Up]] movement which was aimed at exposing sexual harassment and abuse, and creating a society free of gender-based discrimination in the work place.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Letters |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/feb/18/sisters-this-is-our-moment-to-say-times-up |title=Sisters, this is our moment to say Time's Up |date=18 February 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=20 March 2020 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In August 2018, Clarke, as well as [[Gemma Arterton]], [[Lena Headey]], [[Tom Hiddleston]], [[Felicity Jones]], [[Wunmi Mosaku]], [[Florence Pugh]], [[Gemma Chan]], and [[Catherine Tate]], featured in the short film titled ''Leading Lady Parts'' which took aim at the film industry's issue of gender inequality during the casting process.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-gemma-arterton-leading-lady-parts-20180802-story.html |title=Gemma Arterton's Time's Up-inspired short 'Leading Lady Parts' takes aim at the casting process |date=2 August 2018 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Patrick Soon-Shiong#Investments|Nant Capital]]|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, following the announcement of the brain aneurysms she suffered in 2011 and 2013, Clarke launched her own charity SameYou. The charity aims to broaden neurorehabilitation access for young people after a brain injury or stroke.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sameyou.org/ |title=SameYou Charity |website=SameYou |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504051059/https://www.sameyou.org/ |archive-date=4 May 2019 |access-date=6 May 2019}}</ref> On 26 September 2019, she co-hosted a YouTube live stream with Irish YouTuber [[Jacksepticeye]] that raised over \u00a3200,000 for SameYou.<ref name=\"dexerto\">{{Cite news |last=Porter |first=Matt |url=https://www.dexerto.com/entertainment/emilia-clarke-food-challenge-jacksepticeye-goes-epically-wrong-1073232 |title=Emilia Clarke's food challenge with Jacksepticeye goes epically wrong |date=27 September 2019 |work=Dexerto |access-date=31 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927231757/https://www.dexerto.com/entertainment/emilia-clarke-food-challenge-jacksepticeye-goes-epically-wrong-1073232 |archive-date=27 September 2019}}</ref> After the conclusion of the [[Game of Thrones (season 8)|final season]] of ''Game of Thrones'' a fundraiser called \"Justice for Daenerys\" was started in which fans of the show raised over \u00a383,000 for her charity.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gonzales |first1=Erica |title=Emilia Clarke Gets Emotional Responding to Fans Who Fundraised for Her Charity |url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/celebrity/latest/a27682666/emilia-clarke-same-you-fundraising-video-response/ |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=[[Harper's Bazaar]] |publisher=[[Hearst Communications]] |date=31 May 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703041414/https://www.harpersbazaar.com/celebrity/latest/a27682666/emilia-clarke-same-you-fundraising-video-response/ |archivedate=3 July 2019}}</ref> According to the fundraiser creator, the purpose was to collectively show their appreciation for both Clarke, and the character Daenerys Targaryen.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/05/emilia-clarke-charity-fundraiser-interview-creator-elle-ellaria/ |title=Interview with 'Elle Ellaria,' Creator of the Fundraiser for Emilia Clarke's Charity: 'It's a Message of Love & Support' |last=Dwilson |first=Stephanie Dube |date=30 May 2019 |website=[[Heavy.com]] |publisher=Heavy, Inc.|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nClarke lives in [[Hampstead]], London.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Markovitz |first=Benjamin |url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/interviews/a38719/emilia-clarke-swa-2015/ |title=The Gorgeous Balance of Emilia Clarke, Sexiest Woman Alive 2015 |date=13 October 2015 |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |access-date=15 October 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151014125026/http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/interviews/a38719/emilia-clarke-swa-2015/ |archive-date=14 October 2015 |publisher=[[Hearst Communications]]}}</ref> In 2016, she purchased a $4.64{{nbsp}}million house in [[Venice, Los Angeles|Venice Beach]], [[California]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://la.curbed.com/2016/10/13/13279240/game-of-thrones-emilia-clarke-venice-house |title=Emilia Clarke Purchases Venice Beach Mansion |date=13 October 2016 |website=[[Curbed]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161016221354/http://la.curbed.com/2016/10/13/13279240/game-of-thrones-emilia-clarke-venice-house |archive-date=16 October 2016 |access-date=13 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a March 2019 article she wrote for ''[[The New Yorker]]'', she revealed she had a [[subarachnoid haemorrhage]] caused by a ruptured [[aneurysm]], in February 2011. She underwent urgent [[endovascular coiling]] surgery and subsequently suffered from [[aphasia]]; at one point she was unable to recall her own name. She had a second aneurysm surgically treated in 2013.<ref name=\"NY-Surgery\">{{Cite magazine |last=Clarke |first=Emilia |date=21 March 2019 |title=A Battle for My Life |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/personal-history/emilia-clarke-a-battle-for-my-life |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |access-date=22 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nClarke is a [[feminist]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/emilia-clarke-game-of-thrones |title=Emilia Clarke uses gangster rap to get into character |last=McGurk |first=Stuart |date=25 July 2016 |website=[[GQ]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101230623/https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/emilia-clarke-game-of-thrones |archive-date=1 January 2020 |access-date=22 November 2019}}</ref> She was voted the most desirable woman in the world by ''[[AskMen]]'' readers in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2014/02/11/askmen-top-99-most-desirable-women-of-2014-are-/5388193/ |title=Top 99 Most Desirable Women of 2014 are ... |last=Oldenburg |first=Ann |date=11 February 2014 |website=[[USA Today]] |publisher=[[Gannett]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140212012547/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2014/02/11/askmen-top-99-most-desirable-women-of-2014-are-/5388193/ |archive-date=12 February 2014 |access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> In 2015 she was named ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''{{'}}s Sexiest Woman Alive, and was recognized with the ''[[GQ]]'' Woman of the Year Award that same year.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/interviews/a38719/emilia-clarke-swa-2015/ |title=The Gorgeous Balance of Emilia Clarke, Sexiest Woman Alive 2015 |date=13 October 2015 |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |access-date=2 November 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151101161516/http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/interviews/a38719/emilia-clarke-swa-2015/ |archive-date=1 November 2015 |publisher=[[Hearst Communications]]}}</ref> She was also named in ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]''{{'s}} list of Best Dressed Women in 2017.<ref name=\"glamour\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/gallery/best-dressed-women-2017 |title=It's Official: These are the best dressed women of 2017 |date=26 October 2017 |work=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]] |access-date=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220021112/https://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/gallery/best-dressed-women-2017 |archive-date=20 February 2018 |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]}}</ref>\n\nOnce filming concluded on the final season of ''Game of Thrones'', Clarke, as a tribute to her role as Daenerys Targaryen, commemorated her time on the show with a wrist tattoo featuring a trio of flying dragons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/celebrity/latest/a23332545/emilia-clarke-game-of-thrones-tattoo/|title=Emilia Clarke Just Got a Game of Thrones Tattoo and It's So Perfect|last=Greenberg|first=Isabel|date=20 September 2018|website=[[Harper's Bazaar]] |publisher=[[Hearst Communications]]|access-date=2 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524070332/https://www.harpersbazaar.com/celebrity/latest/a23332545/emilia-clarke-game-of-thrones-tattoo/|archive-date=24 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n[[File:Emilia Clarke Cannes 2018.jpg|thumb|alt=Actress Emilia Clarke at the 2018 Cannes Film Festival|Clarke at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable pl