{"title_page": "Buzz Fazio", "text_new": "[[Image:Buzz Fazio 1965.jpg|thumb|Buzz Fazio c. 1965]]\n'''Basil \"Buzz\" Fazio''' (February 7, 1908 &ndash; February 15, 1993) nicknamed the \"Buzzer\" was a pioneer and early American bowling star during the mid-20th century. Known equally for his fierce competitiveness and audience pleasing theatrics, Fazio's professional career spanned from the early 1940s to the late 1960s. The six-time ABC ([[American Bowling Congress]]) and two-time PBA ([[Professional Bowlers Association]]) champion began his career during bowling's golden era of \"Team\" play.\n\n==Early career==\nBorn in [[Aultman, Ohio]], near [[Akron, Ohio|Akron]], Fazio was brought to [[Detroit]] in 1947 to join the fabled [[Stroh Brewing Company|Stroh's]] Beer bowling team. The diminutive Fazio, who stood 5\u2019 6\" and weighed about 140 pounds, captained Stroh's for nine seasons and continued the team's tradition for success started by his predecessor and fellow Hall-of-Famer [[Joe Norris]].\n\nDuring the 1950s, the Fazio led Stroh's Beer squad, featuring [[Lee Jouglard]], [[Tom Hennessy]], [[Pete Carter]], [[Tony Lindemann]], and [[Ed Lubanski]], captured numerous tournaments including the BPAA Team Championships in 1952, 1953 and 1954.<ref name=\"www.bowl.com\">[http://www.bowl.com bowl.com - Official Web Site of the United States Bowling Congress<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Fazio also teamed up with Stroh's teammate [[Tony Lindemann]] to win the BPAA Doubles Championship three times (1951, 1952 and 1954).\n\nBefore the formation of the PBA in 1958, Fazio and his contemporaries competed on TV shows like ''[[Make That Spare]]'', ''Bowling for Dollars'' and ''Championship Bowling'', the latter of which was hosted by Detroit legend Fred Wolf. Among the many bowling highlights in his career, Fazio was the first to roll an 800 series on live TV (802),<ref name=\"www.pba.com\">[http://www.pba.com PBA.com - Official site of the Professional Bowlers Association<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and was the first-ever to roll a [[Perfect game (bowling)|300 game]] in the finals of the BPAA All-Star (predecessor to the [[U.S. Open (bowling)|U.S. Open]]). He also won seven consecutive televised matches in Chicago in 1955.<ref name=\"www.bowl.com\" />\n\nIn 1955, at age 47, Fazio won the [[USBC Masters|ABC Masters Singles Championship]]. Incredibly, he converted ''two'' [[7-10 split]]s on his way to that victory.<ref>Buzz Fazio at rtbot.net [http://www.rtbot.net/buzz_fazio].</ref> He nearly duplicated his Masters championship 13 years later in 1968 when, at age 60, he was runner-up to Pete Tountas.\n\nIn 1957, Fazio left the Stroh's team and moved to [[St. Louis]] to become captain of the restructured  [[Falstaff Beer]] team.\n\n==PBA Tour==\nDuring the 1958 ABC Tournament held in [[Syracuse, NY]], Fazio attended a meeting at the Hotel Syracuse. Sixty men including [[Don Carter (bowler)|Don Carter]], [[Frank Esposito (bowler)|Frank Esposito]], [[Dick Weber]], [[Carmen Salvino]], [[Billy Welu]], [[Steve Nagy (pro bowler)|Steve Nagy]], [[Harry Smith (bowler)|Harry Smith]], [[Ray Bluth]], [[Dick Hoover]], and [[Junie McMahon]] attended. They were there to listen to an Akron attorney named [[Eddie Elias]] speak about starting a Professional Bowlers Association. After listening to his proposal, thirty-three of the men, including the \u201cBuzzer\u201d each contributed $50 to start the organization and the PBA was formed.<ref name=\"www.syracusebowling.com\">[http://www.syracusebowling.com Syracuse Bowling Association<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nFazio captured a pair of PBA titles, both in 1964. His win in [[Sacramento, California]] in December 1964, at the age of 56, made him at the time the oldest man to capture a PBA Tour championship.<ref>[http://pba.com/Tournaments/FullStandings/255 PBA Seasons at www.pba.com]</ref> That record stood until 1995, when PBA star [[John Handegard]] eclipsed the mark by winning the PBA Northwest Classic at age 57 years, 55 days.<ref name=\"www.pba.com\" />\n\n==Awards==\nFazio's bowling accomplishments earned him enshrinement in both the ABC and PBA Halls-of-Fame. A five-time All-American, in 1999 he was ranked #31 bowler of the 20th Century by ''Bowlers Journal.'' In 2020, after great-grandson, Andrew Fazio, rolled 300, the Fazio family became the second family ever to have sanctioned perfect games through four generations. (Buzz-Joseph-Brian-Andrew Fazio)<ref>[6]</ref>\n\n==Retirement==\nAfter retiring from competition, Fazio continued to represent the [[Brunswick Bowling & Billiards|Brunswick Corporation]] as he had for many years as a player. He hosted the PBA Buzz Fazio Open in Battle Creek, MI and in 1973, served as PBA President.\n\nThough slowed by injuries related to an auto accident and subsequent surgeries, Fazio remained involved in the bowling community during retirement. He often participated in local bowling leagues and served as coach and instructor throughout the 1980s and until his death at age 85 in 1993.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fazio, Buzz}}\n[[Category:American ten-pin bowling players|Fazio, Buzz]]\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Buzz Fazio 1965.jpg|thumb|Buzz Fazio c. 1965]]\n'''Basil \"Buzz\" Fazio''' (February 7, 1908 &ndash; February 15, 1993) nicknamed the \"Buzzer\" was a pioneer and early American bowling star during the mid-20th century. Known equally for his fierce competitiveness and audience pleasing theatrics, Fazio's professional career spanned from the early 1940s to the late 1960s. The six-time ABC ([[American Bowling Congress]]) and two-time PBA ([[Professional Bowlers Association]]) champion began his career during bowling's golden era of \"Team\" play.\n\n==Early career==\nBorn in [[Aultman, Ohio]], near [[Akron, Ohio|Akron]], Fazio was brought to [[Detroit]] in 1947 to join the fabled [[Stroh Brewing Company|Stroh's]] Beer bowling team. The diminutive Fazio, who stood 5\u2019 6\" and weighed about 140 pounds, captained Stroh's for nine seasons and continued the team's tradition for success started by his predecessor and fellow Hall-of-Famer [[Joe Norris]].\n\nDuring the 1950s, the Fazio led Stroh's Beer squad, featuring [[Lee Jouglard]], [[Tom Hennessy]], [[Pete Carter]], [[Tony Lindemann]], and [[Ed Lubanski]], captured numerous tournaments including the BPAA Team Championships in 1952, 1953 and 1954.<ref name=\"www.bowl.com\">[http://www.bowl.com bowl.com - Official Web Site of the United States Bowling Congress<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Fazio also teamed up with Stroh's teammate [[Tony Lindemann]] to win the BPAA Doubles Championship three times (1951, 1952 and 1954).\n\nBefore the formation of the PBA in 1958, Fazio and his contemporaries competed on TV shows like ''[[Make That Spare]]'', ''Bowling for Dollars'' and ''Championship Bowling'', the latter of which was hosted by Detroit legend Fred Wolf. Among the many bowling highlights in his career, Fazio was the first to roll an 800 series on live TV (802),<ref name=\"www.pba.com\">[http://www.pba.com PBA.com - Official site of the Professional Bowlers Association<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and was the first-ever to roll a [[Perfect game (bowling)|300 game]] in the finals of the BPAA All-Star (predecessor to the [[U.S. Open (bowling)|U.S. Open]]). He also won seven consecutive televised matches in Chicago in 1955.<ref name=\"www.bowl.com\" />\n\nIn 1955, at age 47, Fazio won the [[USBC Masters|ABC Masters Singles Championship]]. Incredibly, he converted ''two'' [[7-10 split]]s on his way to that victory.<ref>Buzz Fazio at rtbot.net [http://www.rtbot.net/buzz_fazio].</ref> He nearly duplicated his Masters championship 13 years later in 1968 when, at age 60, he was runner-up to Pete Tountas.\n\nIn 1957, Fazio left the Stroh's team and moved to [[St. Louis]] to become captain of the restructured  [[Falstaff Beer]] team.\n\n==PBA Tour==\nDuring the 1958 ABC Tournament held in [[Syracuse, NY]], Fazio attended a meeting at the Hotel Syracuse. Sixty men including [[Don Carter (bowler)|Don Carter]], [[Frank Esposito (bowler)|Frank Esposito]], [[Dick Weber]], [[Carmen Salvino]], [[Billy Welu]], [[Steve Nagy (pro bowler)|Steve Nagy]], [[Harry Smith (bowler)|Harry Smith]], [[Ray Bluth]], [[Dick Hoover]], and [[Junie McMahon]] attended. They were there to listen to an Akron attorney named [[Eddie Elias]] speak about starting a Professional Bowlers Association. After listening to his proposal, thirty-three of the men, including the \u201cBuzzer\u201d each contributed $50 to start the organization and the PBA was formed.<ref name=\"www.syracusebowling.com\">[http://www.syracusebowling.com Syracuse Bowling Association<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nFazio captured a pair of PBA titles, both in 1964. His win in [[Sacramento, California]] in December 1964, at the age of 56, made him at the time the oldest man to capture a PBA Tour championship.<ref>[http://pba.com/Tournaments/FullStandings/255 PBA Seasons at www.pba.com]</ref> That record stood until 1995, when PBA star [[John Handegard]] eclipsed the mark by winning the PBA Northwest Classic at age 57 years, 55 days.<ref name=\"www.pba.com\" />\n\n==Awards==\nFazio's bowling accomplishments earned him enshrinement in both the ABC and PBA Halls-of-Fame. A five-time All-American, in 1999 he was ranked #31 bowler of the 20th Century by ''Bowlers Journal.'' In 2020, after great-grandson, Andrew Fazio, rolled 300, the Fazio family became the second family ever to have sanctioned perfect games through four generations. (Buzz-Joseph-Brian-Andrew Fazio)^6^\n\n==Retirement==\nAfter retiring from competition, Fazio continued to represent the [[Brunswick Bowling & Billiards|Brunswick Corporation]] as he had for many years as a player. He hosted the PBA Buzz Fazio Open in Battle Creek, MI and in 1973, served as PBA President.\n\nThough slowed by injuries related to an auto accident and subsequent surgeries, Fazio remained involved in the bowling community during retirement. He often participated in local bowling leagues and served as coach and instructor throughout the 1980s and until his death at age 85 in 1993.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fazio, Buzz}}\n[[Category:American ten-pin bowling players|Fazio, Buzz]]\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Information Outlet", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards:Reference formatting edited", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buzz_Fazio"}
{"title_page": "Nanosocialism", "text_new": "{{socialism sidebar}}\n{{Nanotech}}\n\n'''Nanosocialism''' refers generally to a set of [[economics|economic theories]] of [[social organization]] advocating [[State (polity)|state]] or [[collective ownership]] and administration of the [[research and development|research, development]] and use of [[nanotechnology]].\n\n== Politics ==\n\n{{further|Regulation of nanotechnology}}\n\nNanosocialism is a stance that favors [[participatory politics]] to guide [[state intervention]] in the effort to manage the transition to a [[society]] revolutionized by [[molecular nanotechnology]].<ref name=\"Berube 1996\">{{cite journal|    author = Berube, David|    title = Nanosocialism|    year = 1996 |   url = http://www.cas.sc.edu/engl/faculty/berube/nanosoc.htm| accessdate=2007-01-30 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061225060622/http://www.cas.sc.edu/engl/faculty/berube/nanosoc.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-12-25}}</ref><ref name=\"Hughes 2001\">{{cite journal|    author = [[James Hughes (sociologist)|Hughes, James]]|    title = Politics of Transhumanism|    year = 2001 |   url = http://www.changesurfer.com/Acad/TranshumPolitics.htm| accessdate=2007-01-26}}</ref>\n\n\"Nanosocialism\" is a term coined by [[David M. Berube]], the associate director of Nanoscience and Technology Studies at the USC NanoCenter, who argues that nanotechnological projections need to be tempered by [[technorealism]] about the [[implications of nanotechnology]] in a [[technocapitalist]] society, but that its [[List of nanotechnology applications|applications]] also offer enormous opportunities for [[abundance (economics)|economic abundance]] and [[social progress]].<ref name=\"Berube 1996\"/><ref name=\"Hughes 2001\"/>\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{unreferenced section|date=July 2012}}\nIn the [[role-playing game]] ''[[Transhuman Space]]'', nanosocialism is described as a descendant of [[infosocialism]], in which [[intellectual property]] is [[nationalization|nationalized]] and freely distributed by the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sjgames.com/gurps/transhuman/|title=Transhuman Space|website=www.sjgames.com|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> It is adopted by some developing nations to counter the hold corporations from wealthier nations have on [[copyright]]s and [[patent]]s. This fictional version of nanosocialism was coined by [[David L. Pulver]], the game's creator, who was unaware that the term had already been used by Berube.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Post-scarcity economy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Socialism}}\n\n[[Category:Political neologisms]]\n[[Category:Technology neologisms]]\n[[Category:Technology in society]]\n[[Category:Nanotechnology]]\n[[Category:Political science terminology]]\n[[Category:Technological utopianism]]\n\n\n{{polisci-stub}}\n{{nano-tech-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Nanotech}}\n\n'''Nanosocialism''' refers generally to a set of [[economics|economic theories]] of [[social organization]] advocating [[State (polity)|state]] or [[collective ownership]] and administration of the [[research and development|research, development]] and use of [[nanotechnology]].\n\n== Politics ==\n\n{{further|Regulation of nanotechnology}}\n\nNanosocialism is a stance that favors [[participatory politics]] to guide [[state intervention]] in the effort to manage the transition to a [[society]] revolutionized by [[molecular nanotechnology]].<ref name=\"Berube 1996\">{{cite journal|    author = Berube, David|    title = Nanosocialism|    year = 1996 |   url = http://www.cas.sc.edu/engl/faculty/berube/nanosoc.htm| accessdate=2007-01-30 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061225060622/http://www.cas.sc.edu/engl/faculty/berube/nanosoc.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-12-25}}</ref><ref name=\"Hughes 2001\">{{cite journal|    author = [[James Hughes (sociologist)|Hughes, James]]|    title = Politics of Transhumanism|    year = 2001 |   url = http://www.changesurfer.com/Acad/TranshumPolitics.htm| accessdate=2007-01-26}}</ref>\n\n\"Nanosocialism\" is a term coined by [[David M. Berube]], the associate director of Nanoscience and Technology Studies at the USC NanoCenter, who argues that nanotechnological projections need to be tempered by [[technorealism]] about the [[implications of nanotechnology]] in a [[technocapitalist]] society, but that its [[List of nanotechnology applications|applications]] also offer enormous opportunities for [[abundance (economics)|economic abundance]] and [[social progress]].<ref name=\"Berube 1996\"/><ref name=\"Hughes 2001\"/>\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{unreferenced section|date=July 2012}}\nIn the [[role-playing game]] ''[[Transhuman Space]]'', nanosocialism is described as a descendant of [[infosocialism]], in which [[intellectual property]] is [[nationalization|nationalized]] and freely distributed by the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sjgames.com/gurps/transhuman/|title=Transhuman Space|website=www.sjgames.com|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> It is adopted by some developing nations to counter the hold corporations from wealthier nations have on [[copyright]]s and [[patent]]s. This fictional version of nanosocialism was coined by [[David L. Pulver]], the game's creator, who was unaware that the term had already been used by Berube.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Post-scarcity economy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Socialism]]\n[[Category:Political neologisms]]\n[[Category:Technology neologisms]]\n[[Category:Technology in society]]\n[[Category:Nanotechnology]]\n[[Category:Political science terminology]]\n[[Category:Technological utopianism]]\n\n\n{{polisci-stub}}\n{{nano-tech-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Piyyas", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nanosocialism"}
{"title_page": "Umbrella man (JFK assassination)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Umbrella Man (disambiguation){{!}}Umbrella Man}}\n{{infobox person\n|name= Umbrella Man\n|image= Umbrella Man.jpg\n|image_size= 200px\n|caption=In the aftermath of the assassination, two men can be seen sitting together on the sidewalk on the right side of the photograph. The \"umbrella man\" is the one in the dark jacket, farthest to the right.\n|birth_name= Louie Steven Witt\n|birth_date= October 20, 1924\n|birth_place= [[Rockwall, Texas]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date= November 17, 2014 (aged 90)\n|death_place= [[Dallas]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n|other_names= Umbrella Man\n|occupation= Rio Grande National Life Insurance Company\n|known for= Witness to John F. Kennedy's assassination\n}}\nThe '''\"umbrella man\"''', identified by the [[United States House Select Committee on Assassinations]] in 1978 as '''Louie Steven Witt''', is a name given to a figure who appears in the [[Zapruder film]], and several other films and photographs, near the [[Stemmons Freeway]] sign within [[Dealey Plaza]] during the [[assassination of John F. Kennedy|assassination of United States President John F. Kennedy]].\n\nWitt is the subject of a 2011 documentary short, ''The Umbrella Man'', by [[Errol Morris]] for ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Umbrella Man|url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/2011/11/21/opinion/100000001183275/the-umbrella-man.html|accessdate=February 17, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 21, 2011|authorlink1=Errol Morris |first1=Errol |last1=Morris}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3LDR5-3zmCk |title=The Umbrella Man: Assassination of JFK |format=Video |via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\n==Speculation==\nA person popularly dubbed the \"umbrella man\" has been the object of much speculation, as he was the only person seen carrying, and opening, an [[umbrella]] on that sunny day. He was also one of the closest bystanders to [[President of the United States|President]] [[John F. Kennedy]] when Kennedy was first struck by a bullet. As [[SS-100-X|Kennedy's limousine]] approached, the man opened up and lifted the umbrella high above his head, then spun or panned the umbrella from east to west (clockwise) as the president passed by him. In the aftermath of the assassination, the \"umbrella man\" sat down on the sidewalk next to another man before getting up and walking towards the [[Texas School Book Depository]].\n\nEarly speculation came from assassination researchers [[Josiah Thompson]] and [[Richard Sprague]] who noticed the open umbrella in a series of photographs. Thompson and Sprague suggested that the \"umbrella man\" may have been acting as a signaler of some kind, opening his umbrella to signal \"go ahead\" and then raising it to communicate \"fire a second round\" to other gunmen.<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.ratical.org/ratville/JFK/TUM.txt | title=The Umbrella System: Prelude to an Assassination | author=Richard E. Sprague and Robert Cutler | journal=[[Gallery (magazine)|Gallery Magazine]] |date=June 1978}}</ref><ref name=\"mcadams\">{{cite web|url=http://mcadams.posc.mu.edu/prouty_tum.htm |title=The Umbrella Man Shooting Darts in Dealey Plaza |publisher=Mcadams.posc.mu.edu |date=1960-07-29 |accessdate=2011-11-29}}</ref> The \"umbrella man\" is depicted as performing such a role in [[Oliver Stone]]'s film ''[[JFK (film)|JFK]]''<ref name=\"Jonsson\">{{cite news |last=Jonsson |first=Patrik |date=November 22, 2013 |title=JFK assassination: Why suspicions still linger about 'Umbrella Man' |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/2013/1122/JFK-assassination-Why-suspicions-still-linger-about-Umbrella-Man |newspaper=[[The Christian Science Monitor]] |location= |accessdate=September 19, 2014}}</ref> and ''[[The X-Files]]'' episode \"[[Musings of a Cigarette Smoking Man]].\"<ref name=\"Musings_of_a_Cigarette_Smoking_Man\">{{cite episode| title=Musings of a Cigarette Smoking Man | series=The X-Files | credits =[[Glen Morgan]] (director and writer) | network = [[Fox Home Entertainment]] | season = 4 | number = 7 }}</ref> Another theory proposed by [[Robert B. Cutler]] and endorsed by Colonel [[L. Fletcher Prouty]] is that the umbrella may have been used to fire a dart with a paralyzing agent at Kennedy to immobilize his muscles and make him a \"sitting duck\" for an assassination.<ref name=\"mcadams\"/>\n\n==Identification==\nAfter an appeal to the public by the [[United States House Select Committee on Assassinations]] (HSCA), Louie Steven Witt came forward in 1978 and claimed to be the \"umbrella man\".<ref name=hscahearings>{{cite web|url=http://history-matters.com/archive/jfk/hsca/reportvols/vol4/html/HSCA_Vol4_0217a.htm |title=House select committee on assassinations testimony, September 25, 1978 |publisher=History-matters.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-04}}</ref> He claimed still to have the umbrella and did not know he had been the subject of controversy. He said that he brought the umbrella simply to heckle Kennedy, whose father, [[Joseph P. Kennedy Sr.|Joseph]], had been a supporter of the Nazi-appeasing British Prime Minister [[Neville Chamberlain]]. By waving a black umbrella, Chamberlain's trademark fashion accessory, Witt said he was protesting the Kennedy family appeasing [[Adolf Hitler]] before [[World War II]]. An umbrella had been used in cartoons in the 1930s to symbolize such appeasement, and Chamberlain often carried an umbrella.<ref name=hscahearings/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcadams.posc.mu.edu/umbrella.gif |title=Example of umbrella used in a 1930s appeasement cartoon |date= |accessdate=2011-11-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/22/opinion/the-umbrella-man.html |title=The Umbrella Man\u2019 |publisher=New York Times |date=November 21, 2011 |accessdate=2011-11-29}}</ref> Kennedy, who wrote a thesis on appeasement while at [[Harvard University|Harvard]], ''[[Why England Slept]]'', might have recognized the symbolism of the umbrella. Black umbrellas had been used in connection with protests against the President before; at the time of the construction of the [[Berlin Wall]], a group of schoolchildren from [[Bonn]] sent the White House an umbrella labeled ''Chamberlain''.<ref>{{cite book  | last1 = Tusa  | first1 = Ann | year = 1997 | title = The Last Division: A History of Berlin, 1945-1989 | publisher = [[Addison Wesley]]  | page = 297 }}</ref>\n\nTestifying before the HSCA, Witt, said \"I think if the [[Guinness World Records|''Guinness Book of World Records'']] had a category for people who were at the wrong place at the wrong time, doing the wrong thing, I would be No. 1 in that position, without even a close runner-up.\"<ref name=hscahearings/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gentry |first1=Margaret |title='Umbrella Man' Theory Destroyed |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=pmdPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cyQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6975%2C3133954 |accessdate=2016-03-16 |work=[[Times-News (Hendersonville, North Carolina)|The Times-News]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=1978-09-26 |location=Hendersonville, N.C. |page=11}}</ref>\n\nWitt died on November 17, 2014.<ref>[http://www.tributes.com/obituary/show/Louie-Steven-Witt-101899572 Obituary]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Badge Man]]\n*[[Three tramps]]\n*[[Babushka Lady]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last1=Cutler |first1=Robert B. |authorlink1=Robert B. Cutler|title=The Umbrella Man: Evidence of Conspiracy'' |publisher=[[The Conspiracy Museum]], Incorporated |year=1995 |origyear=1975 |asin=B004C33O4K}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jfk-online.com/jfk100tum.html The JFK 100: The Umbrella Man]\n* [http://mcadams.posc.mu.edu/dealey.htm#tum JFK Assassination Home Page: The Umbrella Man in Dealey Plaza]\n* [http://mcadams.posc.mu.edu/prouty_tum.htm JFK Assassination Home Page: The Umbrella Man Shooting Darts in Dealey Plaza]\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3LDR5-3zmCk |title=The Umbrella Man: Assassination of JFK |format=Video |via=[[YouTube]]}}\n\n{{Assassination of John F. Kennedy|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories regarding the assassination of John F. Kennedy]]\n[[Category:Witnesses to the assassination of John F. Kennedy]]\n[[Category:Formerly unidentified people]]\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Umbrella Man (disambiguation){{!}}Umbrella Man}}\n{{infobox person\n|name= Umbrella Man\n|image= Umbrella Man.jpg\n|image_size= 200px\n|caption=In the aftermath of the assassination, two men can be seen sitting together on the sidewalk on the right side of the photograph. The \"umbrella man\" is the one in the dark jacket, farthest to the right.\n|birth_name= Louie Steven Witt\n|birth_date= October 20, 1924\n|birth_place= [[Rockwall, Texas]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date= November 17, 2014 (aged 90)\n|death_place= [[Dallas]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n|other_names= Umbrella Man\n|occupation= Rio Grande Insurance Company\n|known for= Witness to John F. Kennedy's assassination\n}}\nThe '''\"umbrella man\"''', identified by the [[United States House Select Committee on Assassinations]] in 1978 as '''Louie Steven Witt''', is a name given to a figure who appears in the [[Zapruder film]], and several other films and photographs, near the [[Stemmons Freeway]] sign within [[Dealey Plaza]] during the [[assassination of John F. Kennedy|assassination of United States President John F. Kennedy]].\n\nWitt is the subject of a 2011 documentary short, ''The Umbrella Man'', by [[Errol Morris]] for ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Umbrella Man|url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/2011/11/21/opinion/100000001183275/the-umbrella-man.html|accessdate=February 17, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 21, 2011|authorlink1=Errol Morris |first1=Errol |last1=Morris}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3LDR5-3zmCk |title=The Umbrella Man: Assassination of JFK |format=Video |via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\n==Speculation==\nA person popularly dubbed the \"umbrella man\" has been the object of much speculation, as he was the only person seen carrying, and opening, an [[umbrella]] on that sunny day. He was also one of the closest bystanders to [[President of the United States|President]] [[John F. Kennedy]] when Kennedy was first struck by a bullet. As [[SS-100-X|Kennedy's limousine]] approached, the man opened up and lifted the umbrella high above his head, then spun or panned the umbrella from east to west (clockwise) as the president passed by him. In the aftermath of the assassination, the \"umbrella man\" sat down on the sidewalk next to another man before getting up and walking towards the [[Texas School Book Depository]].\n\nEarly speculation came from assassination researchers [[Josiah Thompson]] and [[Richard Sprague]] who noticed the open umbrella in a series of photographs. Thompson and Sprague suggested that the \"umbrella man\" may have been acting as a signaler of some kind, opening his umbrella to signal \"go ahead\" and then raising it to communicate \"fire a second round\" to other gunmen.<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.ratical.org/ratville/JFK/TUM.txt | title=The Umbrella System: Prelude to an Assassination | author=Richard E. Sprague and Robert Cutler | journal=[[Gallery (magazine)|Gallery Magazine]] |date=June 1978}}</ref><ref name=\"mcadams\">{{cite web|url=http://mcadams.posc.mu.edu/prouty_tum.htm |title=The Umbrella Man Shooting Darts in Dealey Plaza |publisher=Mcadams.posc.mu.edu |date=1960-07-29 |accessdate=2011-11-29}}</ref> The \"umbrella man\" is depicted as performing such a role in [[Oliver Stone]]'s film ''[[JFK (film)|JFK]]''<ref name=\"Jonsson\">{{cite news |last=Jonsson |first=Patrik |date=November 22, 2013 |title=JFK assassination: Why suspicions still linger about 'Umbrella Man' |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/2013/1122/JFK-assassination-Why-suspicions-still-linger-about-Umbrella-Man |newspaper=[[The Christian Science Monitor]] |location= |accessdate=September 19, 2014}}</ref> and ''[[The X-Files]]'' episode \"[[Musings of a Cigarette Smoking Man]].\"<ref name=\"Musings_of_a_Cigarette_Smoking_Man\">{{cite episode| title=Musings of a Cigarette Smoking Man | series=The X-Files | credits =[[Glen Morgan]] (director and writer) | network = [[Fox Home Entertainment]] | season = 4 | number = 7 }}</ref> Another theory proposed by [[Robert B. Cutler]] and endorsed by Colonel [[L. Fletcher Prouty]] is that the umbrella may have been used to fire a dart with a paralyzing agent at Kennedy to immobilize his muscles and make him a \"sitting duck\" for an assassination.<ref name=\"mcadams\"/>\n\n==Identification==\nAfter an appeal to the public by the [[United States House Select Committee on Assassinations]] (HSCA), Louie Steven Witt came forward in 1978 and claimed to be the \"umbrella man\".<ref name=hscahearings>{{cite web|url=http://history-matters.com/archive/jfk/hsca/reportvols/vol4/html/HSCA_Vol4_0217a.htm |title=House select committee on assassinations testimony, September 25, 1978 |publisher=History-matters.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-04}}</ref> He claimed still to have the umbrella and did not know he had been the subject of controversy. He said that he brought the umbrella simply to heckle Kennedy, whose father, [[Joseph P. Kennedy Sr.|Joseph]], had been a supporter of the Nazi-appeasing British Prime Minister [[Neville Chamberlain]]. By waving a black umbrella, Chamberlain's trademark fashion accessory, Witt said he was protesting the Kennedy family appeasing [[Adolf Hitler]] before [[World War II]]. An umbrella had been used in cartoons in the 1930s to symbolize such appeasement, and Chamberlain often carried an umbrella.<ref name=hscahearings/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcadams.posc.mu.edu/umbrella.gif |title=Example of umbrella used in a 1930s appeasement cartoon |date= |accessdate=2011-11-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/22/opinion/the-umbrella-man.html |title=The Umbrella Man\u2019 |publisher=New York Times |date=November 21, 2011 |accessdate=2011-11-29}}</ref> Kennedy, who wrote a thesis on appeasement while at [[Harvard University|Harvard]], ''[[Why England Slept]]'', might have recognized the symbolism of the umbrella. Black umbrellas had been used in connection with protests against the President before; at the time of the construction of the [[Berlin Wall]], a group of schoolchildren from [[Bonn]] sent the White House an umbrella labeled ''Chamberlain''.<ref>{{cite book  | last1 = Tusa  | first1 = Ann | year = 1997 | title = The Last Division: A History of Berlin, 1945-1989 | publisher = [[Addison Wesley]]  | page = 297 }}</ref>\n\nTestifying before the HSCA, Witt, said \"I think if the [[Guinness World Records|''Guinness Book of World Records'']] had a category for people who were at the wrong place at the wrong time, doing the wrong thing, I would be No. 1 in that position, without even a close runner-up.\"<ref name=hscahearings/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gentry |first1=Margaret |title='Umbrella Man' Theory Destroyed |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=pmdPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cyQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6975%2C3133954 |accessdate=2016-03-16 |work=[[Times-News (Hendersonville, North Carolina)|The Times-News]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=1978-09-26 |location=Hendersonville, N.C. |page=11}}</ref>\n\nWitt died on November 17, 2014.<ref>[http://www.tributes.com/obituary/show/Louie-Steven-Witt-101899572 Obituary]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Badge Man]]\n*[[Three tramps]]\n*[[Babushka Lady]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last1=Cutler |first1=Robert B. |authorlink1=Robert B. Cutler|title=The Umbrella Man: Evidence of Conspiracy'' |publisher=[[The Conspiracy Museum]], Incorporated |year=1995 |origyear=1975 |asin=B004C33O4K}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jfk-online.com/jfk100tum.html The JFK 100: The Umbrella Man]\n* [http://mcadams.posc.mu.edu/dealey.htm#tum JFK Assassination Home Page: The Umbrella Man in Dealey Plaza]\n* [http://mcadams.posc.mu.edu/prouty_tum.htm JFK Assassination Home Page: The Umbrella Man Shooting Darts in Dealey Plaza]\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3LDR5-3zmCk |title=The Umbrella Man: Assassination of JFK |format=Video |via=[[YouTube]]}}\n\n{{Assassination of John F. Kennedy|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories regarding the assassination of John F. Kennedy]]\n[[Category:Witnesses to the assassination of John F. Kennedy]]\n[[Category:Formerly unidentified people]]\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "GothMoth77", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Umbrella_man_(JFK_assassination)"}
